title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.2 CHILD HEALTH

description.narrative: Output 1.2. By 2025, the Government and stakeholders at national and subnational level will have an increased capacity to expand and sustainably provide, while families and communities will have an increased capacity to demand, an essential package of quality preventative, promotive and curative services for infants and young children in development and humanitarian situations, and urban settings, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 1.By 2025, new-borns, children and adolescent boys and girls, especially the most disadvantaged and those living in humanitarian situations, have increased access to and use of quality integrated health, nutrition, HIV and early stimulation services and benefit from a more nurturing, protective and clean environment

description.narrative: The Child Health output met 71% of the 2021 Annual Work Plan targets. This achievement was a result of UNICEF engagement with the government to ensure a conducive enabling environment, health systems strengthening, and leveraging of partner resources to achieve results for children. Although programme implementation was constrained by COVID-19 and its containment measures, UNICEF continued to support the Ministry of Health in policy development, capacity building, quality assurance, resource mobilization and the national COVID-19 response. At sub-national level, UNICEF supported districts to ensure an uninterrupted COVID-19 response, multi-sectoral collaboration and health systems strengthening. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:07/01/2022
